# CI-tuned LeakSanitizer suppressions for tst_workerintegration.
#
# Applied ONLY to the shutdown scenarios (i_shut_*, i_leak_bound), which
# intentionally leave detached QCoro frames at process exit (network-redesign.md
# "Shutdown and task ownership", S1-1/S1-2: a suspended frame is detached, not
# destroyed, and leaks a few hundred bytes). sanitizers.yml runs the
# non-shutdown scenarios (i_cancel_*, i_retention, fullChainStashListSucceeds)
# in a SEPARATE step with no suppression file, so they must exit leak-CLEAN on
# their own.
#
# Scope caveat (why the split matters): these lines match a *substring of an
# allocation-stack frame*, not object reachability from a specific detached
# frame. So within a suppressed scenario, ANY leak allocated beneath one of
# these coroutines is silenced. That is acceptable here only because these
# scenarios are the ones whose whole point is to strand those coroutine frames;
# it is NOT a general "this allocation is fine" statement, which is exactly why
# this file must never be applied to the leak-clean scenarios.
#
# Any leak whose stack falls OUTSIDE this closure — a RateLimitManager, the
# Gate, a QNetworkReply, an unrelated allocation — has a different stack, is NOT
# matched here, and MUST fail the job. That failure IS the I-LEAK-BOUND
# enforcement (docs/design/network-redesign-phase5-verification.md §6): never
# widen this file to silence an unexplained leak, and never suppress the whole
# runner.
#
# Each line is `leak:<substring matched against a frame in the leak stack>`.

# Worker per-fetch coroutines (src/itemsmanagerworker.cpp).
leak:ItemsManagerWorker::FetchStashList
leak:ItemsManagerWorker::FetchCharacterList
leak:ItemsManagerWorker::FetchStash
leak:ItemsManagerWorker::FetchCharacter

# Hub drain/setup coroutines (src/ratelimit/ratelimitmanager.cpp,
# src/ratelimit/ratelimiter.cpp).
leak:RateLimitManager::Drain
leak:RateLimitManager::ProcessEntry
leak:RateLimiter::ProbeEndpoint
